# 1. Overview

The manual implementation consists of a Node.js/Express backend connected to a React + Vite frontend. All user accounts, authentication logic, and article storage are handled locally using a SQLite database. The application meets the core assignment requirements:

- Users can register, log in, and remain authenticated using JWT.
- Authenticated users can post article URLs.
- Users can delete only their own articles.
- An automatically seeded admin account can delete any article.
- Article data persists across runs through SQLite.
---

# 2. Implemented Features

## Backend (Node.js + Express + SQLite)

### Database
- SQLite database (`article_share.db`) auto-created on startup.
- Tables created automatically:
  - `users`
  - `articles`
- Admin account created automatically:
  - Username: `admin`
  - Password: `admin`

### Authentication
- User registration endpoint  
  (`POST /api/auth/register`)
- User login endpoint  
  (`POST /api/auth/login`)
- Password hashing using **bcrypt**
- Token-based authentication using **JWT**
- Middleware to validate JWT on protected routes

### Article Functionality
- Create a new article  
  (`POST /api/articles`)
- View all articles  
  (`GET /api/articles`)
- Delete an article  
  (`DELETE /api/articles/:id`)
- Authorization rules:
  - A normal user may delete **only their own** posts
  - Admin may delete **any** post

### Security Practices
- Passwords never stored in plaintext
- Authentication enforced on write/delete operations
- Role-based access control
- Basic input validation (missing fields, invalid URLs)

---

## 2 Frontend (React + Vite)

The frontend is intentionally simple and minimalistic, as permitted by the assignment.

### Main Features
- Login UI
- Register UI
- LocalStorage used to save/restore JWT tokens
- Form to post a new article
- List of all articles
- Delete buttons for authenticated users

### Interaction With Backend
- Fetches all articles from `/api/articles`
- Sends login and register requests to `/api/auth/*`
- Sends authenticated article creation and deletion requests using `Authorization: Bearer <token>`

### UI Design Choices
- No styling libraries
- Inline, minimal styles
- Single-file React implementation (`App.jsx`)
- Simple "college-project-level" functionality

